{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_0161gcFetRHSLo3xhRqHcY5s","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Nielsen's 10 Usability Heuristics\n2\t\n3\tFoundational UX design principles by Jakob Nielsen (1994), refined from 249 usability problems. Used as the base rubric for heuristic evaluation and automated prototype assessment.\n4\t\n5\t## Key Points\n6\t\n7\t- **1 — Visibility of System Status**: Always inform users about what's happening; feedback should be timely and predictable — builds trust\n8\t- **2 — Match System to Real World**: Use language and concepts familiar to users, not internal jargon; follow real-world conventions and natural mapping\n9\t- **3 — User Control and Freedom**: Provide clear \"emergency exits\" (undo/redo, cancel); prevents users from feeling trapped by accidental actions\n10\t- **4 — Consistency and Standards**: Don't make users guess if different words/actions mean the same thing; follow platform conventions (Jakob's Law: users spend most time on other products)\n11\t- **5 — Error Prevention**: Prevent problems first; two error types — slips (unconscious, inattention) and mistakes (mental model mismatch); use constraints and good defaults\n12\t- **6 — Recognition Rather than Recall**: Make elements/actions/options visible; don't force users to remember info across interface sections; limited short-term memory\n13\t- **7 — Flexibility and Efficiency**: Provide accelerators (shortcuts, gestures) for experts while keeping the interface accessible to novices; allow customization\n14\t- **8 — Aesthetic and Minimalist Design**: Every extra info unit competes with relevant content; not about flat design — about keeping visual elements focused on user goals\n15\t- **9 — Help Recover from Errors**: Error messages in plain language, precisely identify the problem, constructively suggest a solution; use visual treatments to make errors noticeable\n16\t- **10 — Help and Documentation**: Best if no docs needed; when required — searchable, task-focused, concise, with concrete steps\n17\t- Originally developed with Rolf Molich (1990); refined via factor analysis of 249 problems (1994); unchanged since then\n18\t- Severity ratings 1–4 commonly used when applying heuristics to specific interfaces\n19\t\n20\t## Related\n21\t\n22\t- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) — applied these heuristics in an AI model comparison across Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini, and ChatGPT\n23\t- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) — usability dimension is grounded in these heuristics\n24\t- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — automated prototype evaluation uses heuristics as scoring framework\n25\t- [Weekly Design Sync — July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) — team adopted Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n26\t\n27\t## Sources\n28\t\n29\t- https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/\n30\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n31\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e62685c4-83ff-4153-a044-58d10058f32c","uuid":"d8e66cd3-f2b8-4392-881e-f4b3d0072b49","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:04:54.945Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-10-usability-heuristics.md","content":"# Nielsen's 10 Usability Heuristics\n\nFoundational UX design principles by Jakob Nielsen (1994), refined from 249 usability problems. Used as the base rubric for heuristic evaluation and automated prototype assessment.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **1 — Visibility of System Status**: Always inform users about what's happening; feedback should be timely and predictable — builds trust\n- **2 — Match System to Real World**: Use language and concepts familiar to users, not internal jargon; follow real-world conventions and natural mapping\n- **3 — User Control and Freedom**: Provide clear \"emergency exits\" (undo/redo, cancel); prevents users from feeling trapped by accidental actions\n- **4 — Consistency and Standards**: Don't make users guess if different words/actions mean the same thing; follow platform conventions (Jakob's Law: users spend most time on other products)\n- **5 — Error Prevention**: Prevent problems first; two error types — slips (unconscious, inattention) and mistakes (mental model mismatch); use constraints and good defaults\n- **6 — Recognition Rather than Recall**: Make elements/actions/options visible; don't force users to remember info across interface sections; limited short-term memory\n- **7 — Flexibility and Efficiency**: Provide accelerators (shortcuts, gestures) for experts while keeping the interface accessible to novices; allow customization\n- **8 — Aesthetic and Minimalist Design**: Every extra info unit competes with relevant content; not about flat design — about keeping visual elements focused on user goals\n- **9 — Help Recover from Errors**: Error messages in plain language, precisely identify the problem, constructively suggest a solution; use visual treatments to make errors noticeable\n- **10 — Help and Documentation**: Best if no docs needed; when required — searchable, task-focused, concise, with concrete steps\n- Originally developed with Rolf Molich (1990); refined via factor analysis of 249 problems (1994); unchanged since then\n- Severity ratings 1–4 commonly used when applying heuristics to specific interfaces\n\n## Related\n\n- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) — applied these heuristics in an AI model comparison across Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini, and ChatGPT\n- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) — usability dimension is grounded in these heuristics\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — automated prototype evaluation uses heuristics as scoring framework\n- [Weekly Design Sync — July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) — team adopted Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n\n## Sources\n\n- https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n","numLines":31,"startLine":1,"totalLines":31}}}
